<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-04-15T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-04-15T11:00:00-05:00" n="683" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d683">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">890h.01/12: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-04-15T16:00:00+00:00">April 15, 1931—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received April 15—1:30 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>109. Embassy’s despatch 1622, February 3.<note n="1" xml:id="d683fn1">Not
                                printed.</note> I have learned informally that the Afghan Minister
                            desires to call on me in the near future to discuss the question of
                            recognition.</p>
                        <p>Unless otherwise instructed I propose to receive him and to say only that
                            I will report the matter to my Government. An expression of the
                            Department’s views would be appreciated.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Dawes</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>